				<h2>Pros and Cons of Vegan Diet.</h2>
				
				
				<p>Veganism or Vegan Diet has been trending for quite a few years and is one the most vouge diets out there. Hollywood celebrities like Liam Hemsworth, Natalie Portman, Jenna Dewan, and others have further popularized the diet. People might be shocked, but veganism doesn't rob you of your agility or performance. In fact, many NFL, NBA, Premier League, Cricket, and Triathletes attribute their impeccable performance to vegan and plant-based diets.Whether you want to become a vegan for the environment and animal rights or want to try it simply because of the hype, it's imperative to understand the pros and cons of a vegan diet. </p>
				<h3>What is a vegan diet?</h3>
				<p>A vegan diet consists of food primarily made with plants. Vegans must avoid animal products like milk, yogurt/curd, cheese, paneer, meat, and eggs. The diet is rich in fruits, vegetables, beans, nuts, and seeds and is full of essential nutrients like minerals, vitamins, healthful fats, and protein. Yup, you heard it right, protein. So, if you're still debating whether to go vegan or not, follow along. Below are some pros and cons of a vegan diet. Just read through and decide for yourself. </p>
				
				
				<h3>Benefits of a vegan diet: </h3>
								
				<p><b>Diet Quality:</b> A well-balanced vegan diet contains plenty of fresh plant foods, which help create positive health outcomes. These foods also reduce inflammation, helping you recover faster.</p> 

<p><b>Improved cardiovascular health:</b> Increasingly, studies have indicated that a vegan diet improves cardiovascular health. This is because plant-based foods contain lots of antioxidants, phytonutrients, and nitrates. But animal products include lots of pro-inflammatory fat and TMAO, which can exasperate cardiovascular problems. </p>

<p><b>Lower risk of developing type II diabetes:</b> According to several studies, a well-balanced vegan diet helps manage sugar levels. For people suffering from type II diabetes, a vegan diet can control your blood sugar levels better and help boost your mood. </p> 

<p><b>Weight management:</b> Fiber-rich, plant-based, and clean vegan diet keep you full for longer periods, ensuring you don't reach out for those paneer pakodas. Abstaining from high-fat and high-calorie animal products helps you lose weight. </p>

<p><b>Lower cholesterol and LDL levels:</b> Meat and dairy products have a high saturated fat content, leading to high LDL levels. So, a plant-based vegan diet help lower your LDL levels and cholesterol.  </p>

<p><b>Easing off some autoimmune diseases:</b> The anti-inflammatory property of a vegan diet also relieves some symptoms of autoimmune diseases like rheumatoid arthritis. Read what Serena Williams has to say about it. 
</p>
				
				<h3>Drawbacks of a vegan diet:</h3>
			<p><b>
Processed vegan food:</b> The alternative meat market is growing at an exponential rate. Most of these meat alternatives like faux chicken fingers, fish fillet, and burgers are highly processed, lack essential nutrients, and have high-fat content. </p>

<p><b>Lack of essential nutrients:</b> Though highly healthy, a vegan diet may deprive you of some crucial nutrients like calcium, which is required for bone and teeth health. B-12 and protein are other essential nutrients obtained from animals and may be lacking in a vegan diet. </p>

<p><b>Social Isolation:</b> Thanks to Impossible and Beyond food, the vegan food landscape is evolving quickly. But there is no denying that it is still challenging to find vegan options at restaurants and parties. Due to this, vegans may avoid social gatherings, leading to significant social isolation.   </p>

<p>Just like every coin has two sides, so does the vegan diet. While it's uber-popular and healthy, it's essential to keep the drawbacks in mind as well. When opting for a vegan diet, make sure to choose a well-balanced vegan diet. Remember to stay away from processed meat alternatives.
</p>
